I"²<p>If every seven years the human body has a renewed set of cells, and if <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/memory-is-perception-of-structural-artifacts">memory is based on structural artifacts</a>, then how come we remember old memories? <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/parallel-distributed-processing-is-resilient-and-efficient">Parallel distributed processing</a>, coupled with adult neurogenesis and synaptogenesis, provide the necessary redundancy for handling this continuous neuron replacement. By <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/selectively-sampling-dimensions-facilitates-manifold-definition">cross-referencing sparse representations</a>, psychological continuity easily bridges episodes of isolated cell death. This <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/machine-learning-ignores-progressive-nature-of-human-learning">long-term progressive aspect is generally ignored in machine learning</a>.</p>
